WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.989
Let's use particles to explain why solids, liquids, and
gases behave so differently. Same idea, three very
different results.

2
00:00:10.989 --> 00:00:18.863
A solid keeps its shape. A metal spoon does not slowly
pour off the table, which is helpful at lunch.

3
00:00:18.863 --> 00:00:32.185
In the particle model, solid particles are packed close
together in a regular pattern. They vibrate in place, but
they do not wander off. Picture a crowd holding hands and

4
00:00:32.185 --> 00:00:39.929
A liquid keeps its volume but changes shape. Pour water
from a bottle into a glass: same amount, new shape.

5
00:00:39.929 --> 00:00:47.851
Liquid particles are still close together, but they can
slide past each other. No fixed pattern, no fixed shape.

6
00:00:47.851 --> 00:00:57.133
A gas spreads out to fill whatever space it gets. Air
fills a balloon. Pop the balloon and the gas does not stay
in a polite balloon-shaped lump.

7
00:00:57.133 --> 00:01:08.910
Gas particles are far apart and zooming in all directions,
bouncing off each other and the walls. Mostly, a gas is
empty space with particles racing through it.

8
00:01:08.910 --> 00:01:21.851
Heating gives particles more energy, so they move more.
Give a solid enough heat and its particles shake free of
their fixed positions. That is melting: solid to liquid.

9
00:01:21.851 --> 00:01:35.426
Cooling removes energy. Slow a liquid's particles down
enough and they settle back into a pattern. That is
freezing: liquid to solid. Same particles, different

10
00:01:35.426 --> 00:01:51.346
Evaporation is liquid to gas, and it can happen at the
surface without boiling. A wet towel dries because water
particles at the surface gain enough energy to escape into

11
00:01:51.346 --> 00:02:05.447
Condensation is gas to liquid. Water vapour hits a cold
mirror, its particles slow down, huddle together, and
become tiny droplets. That is the fog after a hot shower.

12
00:02:05.447 --> 00:02:17.472
Now you can predict. Particles locked in a pattern: keeps
its shape. Close but sliding: it flows. Far apart and
zooming: it spreads to fill the container.

13
00:02:17.472 --> 00:02:30.697
It explains the balloon, too. Blow in air and you add gas
particles, which push outward into every bit of available
space. Balloons are just particle containers with stretch.

14
00:02:30.697 --> 00:02:43.584
And it explains a drying puddle. The water is not being
deleted. Surface particles escape into the air. The puddle
shrinks because its particles left, not because they

15
00:02:43.584 --> 00:03:00.391
Here is a common mistake the model prevents: melting does
not mean turning into water. Wax melts. Butter melts. Iron
melts, at a temperature you should not test at home. The

16
00:03:00.391 --> 00:03:12.187
Test the model. Why does a liquid pour? Its particles
slide past each other. Why does a spoon keep its shape?
Its particles are held in a fixed arrangement.

17
00:03:12.187 --> 00:03:26.081
Why can you squash air in a syringe but not water? Gas
particles have lots of empty space between them, so there
is room to push them closer. Liquid particles are already

18
00:03:26.081 --> 00:03:38.869
The model's real power: it connects what you can see to
what you cannot. Pouring, spreading, drying, fogging,
melting, freezing - one invisible explanation for all of

19
00:03:38.869 --> 00:03:49.383
It also keeps track of mass. When a puddle evaporates, the
water particles move into the air. They have travelled;
they have not vanished.

20
00:03:49.383 --> 00:04:05.134
One warning. Do not imagine water particles as tiny wet
drops or ice particles as tiny ice cubes. The dots in the
model show spacing and movement. They are not microscopic

21
00:04:05.134 --> 00:04:14.609
The chemist's move: when a state changes, don't ask what
the stuff looks like. Ask how its particles are arranged
and how they are moving.
